In Domesday we find these tenants spoken of as sochemanni, socrnanni, or liberi socmamn'. The derivation of the word has given rise to much controversy ε . . . but there can be little question that it is connected with soca, soen, ‘jurisdiction,' from A„-S. secan, ‘to seekz’ The free land- owners had probably by the time of the Conquest been brought nearly universally into the condition of persons owing suit or attendance at the court of some great man. Thus the soclaemanm· are probably the free suitors or attendants (secta, sequor) of the lord’s court, who came in process of time to be regarded as tenants holding in socaye, by the tenure of such suit or service. The services to which they were bound seem to have been usually fixed or certain, and not capable of being exacted arbitrarily by the lord‚ such as the rendering of a certain amount of agricultural service, or having a fixed rent in money or produce. Sometimes a free tenant would only be bound by the cath oi fealty. In process oi time the nature of the services rendered, especially the characteristic oi fixity or certainty, came to be regarded as the mark of a distinct species of freehold tenure called free socage.

“ Socage tenure is thus described by Lyttleton, who wrote in the reign of Edward 1v. :—‘ Tenure in socage is where the tenant holdeth of his lord the tenancy by certain service for all manner of services, so that the service be not knight’s service.
